node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Nicole Angemi, MS, PA (ASCP) on July 26, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Mystery diagnosis: Labiaplasty! @mrs_angemi angemi 12 10 9 8 1 9 5 SteriMarker riPen'.

node.text: The labia minora are the 2 inner lips (right and left) that surround the opening of the vagina. Both labia can be large and hang lower than the labia majora (outer lips). Other times the inner labia can be asymmetrical. This can not only cause self-consciousness about the appearance of the genitalia, but it can also cause extreme discomfort. This patient’s inner labia would fall outside of her underwear while cycling and would get stuck in her vagina during sex. Everyday her labia caused her discomfort, like chafing just from walking. She decided to have a procedure called a labiaplasty to remove the hanging tissue. She is expected to heal within 4-6 weeks where she can resume her normal exercise and sexual activity.

node.text:
This patient was in Hawaii for a wedding. She went swimming in the ocean and got what she thought was a little scrape on the top of her foot from coral on the ocean floor. The scrape started to get worse over the course of the next couple of days, but she did not seek medical attention because of the wedding activities. 2 days later, she returned from her trip and had to go right to work. At this point her foot was in so much pain she couldn’t keep it in a shoe. She was sent to the emergency room by her employer and there she was diagnosed with necrotizing fasciitis. Necrotizing fasciitis is commonly called flesh eating bacteria. This kind of tissue infection can be caused by many kinds of bacteria. When this happens, the bacteria release toxins that cause death to the skin and underlying tissue. This type of infection can get into the body rapidly so it is important that it is treated aggressively in a timely manner. Her doctors said she was lucky, if she did not come in when she did for treatment, she may have lost her foot and maybe even her life! 
Photo: @luv_me_doo

node.text:
When this patient was 15 years old, she went to the dentist to have multiple cavities filled. She was completely numb for the procedure. Suddenly her dentist said “hold on, don’t swallow” and reflexively the first thing she did was swallow! What she swallowed was a piece of a dental tool similar to a drill bit called a dental bur. She went to the emergency room and had this x-ray done that showed the dental bur. Doctors decided to monitor her and have her check her stools. She never found the dental bur but a follow up x-ray showed it was gone from her body! 
Photo: @cassidyonley

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Nicole Angemi, MS, PA (ASCP) on July 05, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'angemi Mystery diagnosis: Tummy tuck necrosis!'.

node.text: This patient is a healthy mom in her 40’s (non-smoker) who wanted to get a tummy tuck to remove loose skin. She did her research and went to a surgeon with 25+ years of experience who also had good ratings. She had her surgery and initially everything seemed to be fine, but the surgical binder she was wearing felt like it was put on too tight. By day 3 she called her surgeon and asked to loosen it because she was having difficulty inhaling and exhaling. On day 6 she had her post op appointment. When her doctor removed the binder, a nasty smell filled the room and the her wounds looked infected. The doctor wasn’t overly concerned about the way the wound was healing, gave her an antibiotic cream, and told her to put maxi pads over the wound. She was very worried about the unusual foul smell coming from the wound and went to the emergency room for another opinion. The ER diagnosed her with tissue necrosis (death), voiced their concerns to her surgeon and the surgeon agreed to do another surgery on her. The surgeon did a second surgery on the original incision to remove the dead tissue and placed a wound vac to promote healing. The new incision also became infected and put her in the hospital where she required IV antibiotics. Months after her original surgery she is finally healing and is left with some pretty large scars. There are risks with any surgery, but in this case the surgeon’s delay in identifying a problem could have cost this patient her life. Always remember to listen to your body if you think something is not right, you know your body better than anyone else!

node.text:
A Buschke-Lowenstein tumor is another name for a warty or verrucous cancerous tumor that grows around the genitals. Most of these cancers are caused by the HPV virus. This case is a 36 year male who presented with a lesion around his anus. Doctors removed some of the top of the lesion for hygienic reasons. He came back within a month and the mass grew much bigger. It was determined it was a very invasive cancer that they were not able to remove. He was given palliative care and was dead within 7 months.
For more GROSS pathology check out The Gross Room! This week’s Celebrity Death Dissection: The Golden Girls!🔪
